value.value: This gene may be involved in both chromatin assembly and the inhibition of calcineurin-dependent signaling.

Human CABIN1 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 22q11.23 and is approximately 167 kb in length. This allele, which encodes calcineurin-binding protein cabin-1, may play a role in the negative regulation of calcineurin-mediated signaling.
Calcineurin-binding protein cabin-1 (2220 aa, ~246 kDa) is encoded by the human CABIN1 gene. This protein may be involved in both calcineurin binding and chromatin assembly.

label.value: Fallopian Tube High Grade Serous Adenocarcinoma

value.value: A rapidly growing serous adenocarcinoma that arises from the fallopian tube. It is characterized by the presence of high grade cytologic features and frequent mitotic figures.

label.value: Low Grade Fallopian Tube Serous Adenocarcinoma

value.value: A slow-growing serous adenocarcinoma that arises from the fallopian tube. It is characterized by the presence of low grade cytologic features and infrequent mitotic figures.
This gene plays a role in peptidyl-tyrosine dephosphorylation.

Human PTPN21 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 14q31.3 and is approximately 89 kb in length. This allele, which encodes tyrosine-protein phosphatase non-receptor type 21 protein, is involved in protein dephosphorylation.
A type of motor neuron, found in the ventral horn of the spinal cord, that innervates intrafusal muscle fibers of neuromuscular spindles to help regulate skeletal muscle tone.
Tyrosine-protein phosphatase non-receptor type 21 (1174 aa, ~133 kDa) is encoded by the human PTPN21 gene. This protein plays a role in dephosphorylation of phosphotyrosines.
Benign proliferation of the fallopian tube epithelium.
An abscess involving the distal fallopian tube and ovary. It is caused by pelvic inflammatory disease or other infections.
Metaplastic mucinous changes in the fallopian tube epithelium. It may be seen in association with gynecological, appendiceal, or colonic mucinous tumors, or chronic inflammation.
An exceedingly rare lymphoma that arises from the fallopian tube.
A carcinoma that arises from the head and neck and has spread from the original site of growth to another anatomic site.
This gene is involved in vesicular transport between the endoplasmic reticulum and the Golgi.

Human NAPA wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 19q13.33 and is approximately 28 kb in length. This allele, which encodes alpha-soluble NSF attachment protein, plays a role in intracellular vesicle transport.
Alpha-soluble NSF attachment protein (295 aa, ~33 kDa) is encoded by the human NAPA gene. This protein is involved in the transport of vesicles between the endoplasmic reticulum and Golgi.
A rare non-invasive tumor that arises from the broad ligament. It is characterized by the presence of serous epithelial cell proliferation and cytological atypia.
A nerve cell that uses nitric oxide as its neurotransmitter.
This gene plays a role in microtubule dynamics.

Human MARK2 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 11q13.1 and is approximately 72 kb in length. This allele, which encodes serine/threonine-protein kinase MARK2 protein, is involved in both protein phosphorylation and microtubule dynamics.
Serine/threonine-protein kinase MARK2 (788 aa, ~88 kDa) is encoded by the human MARK2 gene. This protein plays a role in both microtubule dynamics and serine/threonine phosphorylation.
This gene is involved in endocytosis and recycling of the plasma membrane.
Human EHD1 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 11q13 and is approximately 37 kb in length. This allele, which encodes EH domain-containing protein 1, plays a role in endocytic recycling.
EH domain-containing protein 1 (534 aa, ~61 kDa) is encoded by the human EHD1 gene. This protein is involved in plasma membrane endocytosis and recycling.
A rare serous cystadenoma arising from the broad ligament.
A rare serous cystadenofibroma arising from the broad ligament.
A rare serous adenofibroma arising from the broad ligament.
A rare serous adenocarcinoma that arises from the broad ligament.
An axon that projects from a nerve cell body within an autonomic ganglion and innervates an effector cell within a target organ.

label.value: Low Grade Broad Ligament Serous Adenocarcinoma

value.value: A slow-growing serous adenocarcinoma that arises from the broad ligament. It is characterized by the presence of low grade cytologic features and infrequent mitotic figures.

label.value: High Grade Broad Ligament Serous Adenocarcinoma

value.value: A rapidly growing serous adenocarcinoma that arises from the broad ligament. It is characterized by the presence of high grade cytologic features and frequent mitotic figures.
The flesh of animals used as food.
Meat that has been modified to either extend its shelf life or change its taste.
This gene may play a role in both fat digestion and antimicrobial activity.

A derived program of the National Cancer Institute's Biorepositories and Biospecimen Research Branch (NCI BBRB) that carries out specialized biospecimen and data procurements to support biospecimen science activities. The caHUB network consists of Biospecimen Source Sites (BSSs), The Comprehensive Biospecimen Resource (CBR), The Comprehensive Data Resource (CDR), The Pathology Resource Center (PRC), and Molecular Analysis Facilities (MAFs).

Human NTS wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 12q21 and is approximately 9 kb in length. This allele, which encodes neurotensin/neuromedin N protein, may be involved in both antimicrobial activity and fat digestion.
A protein encoded by the NTS gene.
Neurotensin/neuromedin N (170 aa, ~20 kDa) is encoded by the human NTS gene. This protein may play a role in both the digestion of fat in the gut and anti-bacterial/fungal activity.

A program designed to systematically investigate the effects of individual pre-analytical factors on the molecular profiles of biospecimens. The results of this study will be used to develop evidence-based protocols and best practices for optimal collection, processing, and storage of biospecimens.

An axon that projects from a nerve cell body within a parasympathetic ganglion and innervates an effector cell within a target organ. Postganglionic parasympathetic fibers use acetylcholine as transmitters, sometimes with peptide cotransmitters.
Neurotensin (13 aa, ~2 kDa) is encoded by the human NTS gene. This protein may be involved in the regulation of fat metabolism in the gut.
Neuromedin N (5 aa, ~1 kDa) is encoded by the human NTS gene. This protein may play a role in antimicrobial activity.
This gene is involved in neuropeptide signaling.

A neoplasm that arises from the broad or other uterine ligaments and is characterized by the absence of atypical or malignant cytological and architectural features, and absence of invasive features or metastatic potential.
Human PENK wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 8q12.1 and is approximately 10 kb in length. This allele, which encodes proenkephalin-A protein, plays a role in opioid receptor signaling.
A protein encoded by the PENK gene.
Proenkephalin-A (267 aa, ~31 kDa) is encoded by the human PENK gene. This protein is involved in opioid receptor signaling.
Met-enkephalin (5 aa, ~1 kDa) is encoded by the human PENK and POMC genes. This protein plays a role in the activation of delta opioid receptors.
A primary or metastatic malignant neoplasm that affects the broad or other uterine ligaments.
